  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Climate Change Supplementary Grant</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Current tourism activity often impacts badly on the environment &#x2013; for example collection of shells which are predators of sea urchin and starfish is leading to extensive reef destruction.  Hotel water use is destroying plants and animals tourists come to see. This new funding will significantly develop and expand the existing environmental and climate change focus of the project.  The additional climate elements will provide alternative sources of income, for example through crab and shrimp farms in mangrove swamps; beekeeping; and work in environmental protection.  Training and equipment will be provided to demonstrate these activities, with loans from the main programme available to others who wish to replicate the initiatives. Solar panels, fuel efficient stoves and other technologies will be provided (through funding from the Welsh Government).  This will be underpinned by practical work in all schools, with extensive teacher training, which will develop an understanding and ownership of the value of the children&#x2019;s own environment, leading to long term stewardship.  The project has an existing link between 40 schools in Zanzibar and Wales, which will be greatly enhanced by adding a climate change focus. The project will work with local government, decision makers, and tourist industry to build greater awareness of the necessity to build policy at all levels.</narrative>
  </description>
